Taxonomic catalogue of Heliconiinae

06 January 2025

Order: Lepidoptera Linnaeus, 1758

Family: Nymphalidae Rafinesque, 1815

Subfamily: Heliconiinae Swainson, 1822

Resources:

Tribe Acraeini

Type genus: Acraea Fabricius, 1807

Classification: The tribe Acraeini is divided into eight genera (Williams and Hennig 2023): Acraea, Actinote, Bematistes, Cethosia, Rubraea, Stephenia, Telchinia and Tildia.

References: Penz and Peggie (2003) (phylogeny); Vane-Wright and Jong (2003) (Sulawesi); Silva-Brandão et al. (2008) (phylogeny); Henning and Williams (2010) (taxonomy); Timmermans et al. (2016) (phylogeny); Pierre (2020 a) (Uganda); Lang et al. (2022) (taxonomy; China); Williams and Hennig (2023) (taxonomy)

Genus Acraea

Genus: Acraea Fabricius, 1807

Type species: Acraea horta Linnaeus, 1764; original combination: Papilio horta Linnaeus, 1764

Synonyms:

  • Aphanopeltis Mabille, 1887. Type species: Acraea horta Linnaeus, 1764; original combination: Papilio horta Linnaeus, 1764. Refs.: Mabille (1886): 85
  • Phanopeltis Mabille, 1887. Type species: Acraea ranavalona Boisduval, 1833; original combination: Acraea ranavalona Boisduval, 1833. Refs.: Mabille (1886): 84
  • Solenites Mabille, 1887. Type species: Acraea igati Boisduval, 1833; original combination: Acraea igati Boisduval, 1833. Refs.: Mabille (1886): 82
  • Miyana Fruhstorfer, 1914. Type species: Acraea moluccana Felder, 1860; original combination: Acraea moluccana Felder, 1860. Refs.: Fruhstorfer (1912 a): 743

References: Hennig (1993 a); Williams and Hennig (2010); Pierre and Bernaud (2012) (taxonomy, phylogeny); Pierre and Bernaud (2013); Williams and Hennig (2020); Williams and Hennig (2023) (taxonomic revision)

Genus Actinote

Genus: Actinote Hübner [1819]

Type species: Actinote thalia (Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio thalia Linnaeus, 1758

Synonyms:

  • Calornis Billberg, 1820. Type species: Actinote thalia (Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio thalia Linnaeus, 1758. Refs.: Billberg (1820): 77
  • Abananote Potts, 1943. Type species: Actinote abana (Hewitson, 1868); original combination: Acraea abana Hewitson, 1868. Refs.: Potts (1943): 31 (as subgenus)
  • Altinote Potts, 1943. Type species: Actinote neleus (Latreille, [1813]); original combination: Heliconius neleus Latreille, [1813]. Refs.: Potts (1943): 31

References: Hübner ([1819]): 27

Genus Telchinia

Genus: Telchinia Hübner [1819]

Type species: Telchinia serena (Fabricius, 1775); original combination: Papillio serena Fabricius, 1775

Synonyms:

  • Hyalites Doubleday [1848]. Type species: Telchinia encedon (Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio lycia Fabricius, 1758. Refs.: Doubleday ([1848]): 140
  • Gnesia Doubleday [1848]. Type species: Telchinia circeis (Drury, 1782); original combination: Papilio circeis Drury, 1782. Refs.: Doubleday ([1848]): 141
  • Pareba Doubleday [1848]. Type species: Telchinia issoria Hübner, [1819]; original combination: Papilio vesta Fabricius, 1787. Refs.: Doubleday ([1848]): 142
  • Planema Doubleday [1848]. Type species: Telchinia lycoa (Godart, 1819); original combination: Acraea lycoa Godart, 1819. Refs.: Doubleday ([1848]): 140

References: Hübner ([1819]): 27

Genus Tildia

Genus: Tildia Williams & Henning, 2023

Type species: Tildia zetes (Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio zetes Linnaeus, 1758

Synonyms: None

References: Williams and Hennig (2023)

Tribe Argynnini

Type genus: Argynnis [Fabricius], 1807

Classification: The tribe Argynnini is divided into four subtribes and eight genera (Simonsen 2006 a; Simonsen et al. 2006):

  • Subtribe Argynnina: Argynnis, Brenthis, Issoria

  • Subtribe Boloriina: Boloria (monobasic)

  • Subtribe Euptoietina: Euptoieta (monobasic)

  • Subtribe Yrameina: Yramea (monobasic)

  • Genus Pardopsis (no subtribe assigned).

References: Warren (1944) (taxonomy); dos Passos and Grey (1945 a) (taxonomy); Warren et al. (1946) (taxonomy); Warren (1955) (taxonomy); Lamas (2004) (Neotropics); Penz and Peggie (2003) (phylogeny); Simonsen (2006 a) (taxonomy, phylogeny); Simonsen et al. (2006) (phylogeny)

Synonyms: None

References: Fabricius (1807): 283; De Moya et al. (2017) (phylogeny); Zhang et al. (2020) (genome phylogeny)

Butterflies (6): 109, figs. 10 ♂ D, 11 ♂ V. dos Passos and Grey (1947), Am. Mus. Novit. (1370): 15, designated a “lectotype” (in MGCL), but this is invalid (Code Article 74.2). Type loc.: St. Margarets River.near Sept-Iles along a river that was called Riviere Sainte-Marguerite; Quebec” This river was dammed near its confluence with the St. Laurence River, and the resulting reservoir is called Lac-Walker. Refs.: Duponchel, [1832], In: Godart, Hist. Nat. Lepid. 1(Diurnes), Suppl. 1(6): 127-128, no. 45, pl. 20, no. 4 ♂ V. “Both Duponchel [1832] ibid., and Boisduval [1833], Icon. Hist. Lépid. Europ. 1(10): 98, pl. 20, figs. 5 ♂ D, 6 ♂ V, cited “M. Sommer” as the source of the specimens described. Sommer has been noted as a source of many butterflies from Labrador (e.g., Boisduval and Le Conte [1830], Hist. Lépid. Amér. sept. (8): 66-67, Staudinger (1857), Stettiner Entomol. Ztg. 18(7-9): 300-301, and Hemming (1937), Hübner 2: 123). Scudder (1868), Proc. Boston Soc. Nat. Hist. 11: 33, and Aurivillius (1889), Bih. K. svenska VetenskAkad. Handl. 15(4)(1): 9-10 , fig. 1 VHW, referred to samples from Labrador as boisduvalii. Examination of the type(s), if extant, is needed; if there are no syntypes, the designation of a neotype may be required”.

Tribe Heliconiini

Type genus: Heliconius Kluk, 1780

Classification: The tribe Heliconiini is divided into eight genera based on morphological characters (Michener 1942 a): Agraulis (8 species), Dione (3 species), Dryadula (1 species), Dryas (4 species), Eueides (12 species), Heliconius (47 species), Philaethria (10 species) and Podotricha (2 species).

Characteristics: Larvae are spiny and feed on Passiflora (Passifloraceae).

Phylogenetic relationships: Extensive historical and on-going gene flow in this group makes phylogenetic inference challenging. Molecular phylogenies support the eight genera as monophyletic clades, but the relationships between many genera require further investigation.

Distribution: Neotropics; see occurrence maps by Neil Rosser

References: Michener (1942 a) (keys); Emsley (1963); Emsley (1965); Brown Jr. (1976); Brown (1981) (review); Brown and Fernández Yepez (1984) (Venezuela); Brown Jr. et al. (1992) (chromosomes); Penz and Peggie (2003) (phylogeny); Kozak et al. (2015) (molecular phylogeny); Kozak et al. (2021) (genome phylogeny); Cicconardi et al. (2023) (genome phylogeny)

Genus Heliconius

Genus: Heliconius Kluk, 1780

Type species: Heliconius charithonia (Linnaeus, 1767); original combination: Papilio charithonia Linnaeus, 1767

Synonyms:

  • Heliconius Latreille [1804]. Type species: Heliconius charithonia (Linnaeus, 1767); original combination: Papilio charithonia Linnaeus, 1767. Refs.: Latreille (1804): 185
  • Migonitis Hübner, 1816. Type species: Heliconius erato (Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio erato (Linnaeus, 1764). Refs.: Hübner (1816): 12
  • Sunias Hübner, 1816. Type species: Heliconius melpomene (Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio melpomene Linnaeus, 1758. Refs.: Hübner (1816): 12
  • Ajantis Hübner, 1816. Type species: Heliconius sapho (Linnaeus, 1782); original combination: Papilio sapho Linnaeus, 1782. Refs.: Hübner (1816): 13
  • Apostraphia Hübner, 1816. Type species: Heliconius charithonia (Linnaeus, 1767); original combination: Papilio charithonia Linnaeus, 1767. Refs.: Hübner (1816): 13
  • Sicyonia Hübner, 1816. Type species: Heliconius sara (Fabricius, 1793); original combination: Papilio rhea Cramer, 1775. Refs.: Hübner (1816): 13
  • Heliconia Latreille, 1818. Type species: Heliconius charithonia (Linnaeus, 1767); original combination: Papilio charithonia Linnaeus, 1767. Refs.: NA
  • Laparus Billberg, 1820. Type species: Heliconius doris (Linnaeus, 1771); original combination: Papilio doris (Linnaeus, 1771). Refs.: Billberg (1820): 77
  • Crenis Hübner, 1821. Type species: Heliconius doris doris (Linnaeus, 1771); original combination: Crenis brylle Hübner (1821). Refs.: NA
  • Phlogris Hübner [1825]. Type species: Heliconius melpomene (Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio melpomene Linnaeus, 1758. Refs.: NA
  • Sicyonia Hübner [1826] Refs.: An unjustified emendation of Sicyonia Hübner, 1816
  • Podalirius Gistel, 1848. Type species: Heliconius charithonia (Linnaeus, 1767); original combination: Papilio charithonia Linnaeus, 1767. Refs.: Gistel (1848): ix
  • Blanchardia Buchecker [1880]. Type species: Heliconius hecuba (Hewitson, [1858]); original combination: Blanchardia dismorphia Buchecker [1880]. Refs.: NA

Phylogenetic relationships: Molecular phylogenetic studies using a small number of loci (Brower 1994; Brower and Egan 1997; Beltrán et al. 2002; Beltrán et al. 2007; Kozak et al. 2015) supported at least six clades within Heliconius: Aoede, Doris, Wallacei, Melpomene (including the silvaniforms), Erato and Sara. The relationships among these groups and among species within each group remain uncertain.

Distribution: Widespread across the Neotropics

References: Kluk (1802): 82; Emsley (1965); ICZN (2014): 204

Genus Philaethria

Genus: Philaethria Billberg, 1820

Type species: Philaethria dido (Linnaeus, 1763); original combination: Papilio dido Linnaeus, 1763

Synonyms:

  • Metamandana Stichel [1908]. Type species: Philaethria dido (Linnaeus, 1763); original combination: Papilio dido Linnaeus, 1763. Refs.: Stichel (1908): 6

Classification: Species of Philaethria have distinctive green and black wing patterns, similar to Siproeta stelenes (malachite; Nymphalidae: Nymphalinae: Victorinini) that is also found throughout the Neotropics, but they have distinct wing shapes.

Phylogenetic relationships: Phylogenetic relationships among the species remain to be investigated.

Distribution: Widespread across the Neotropics

References: Billberg (1820): 77; Michener (1942 a) (key to genus); Constantino and Salazar (2010) (key to species)

10 species:

  • andrei Brévignon, 2002

    • ssp. andrei Brévignon, 2002. Type loc.: Carapa, Macouria, French Guyana (LCB). Distr.: Lower Amazon basin in northern South America from Venezuela (El Manteco, Bolivar) to French Guiana (Carapa, Macouria) and northern Brazil (Marajó). Altitude 100–200m. Rainforest habitats. Host plants: Passiflora laurifolia. Refs.: Brevignon (2002), Constantino and Salazar (2010) (to subspecies). Ety.: André Brévignon

    • ssp. orinocensis Constantino & Salazar, 2010. Type loc.: Delta Amacuro, Venezuela (MIZA; paratypes: JCSC). Distr.: Open grasslands in the Orinoco river basin in Venezuela up to 100m above sea level and in the state of Bolivar (rio Caura). Refs.: Constantino and Salazar (2010): 16. Ety.: Orinoco River

  • browni Constantino & Salazar, 2010. Type loc.: Barinitas, Barinas, Venezuela (MIZA; paratypes: CFC). Distr.: East slope of the Cordillera de Merida in Barinas, Venezuela. 600-1200m above sea level. Premontane forest habitats. Refs.: Constantino and Salazar (2010): 23. Ety.: Keith S. Brown

  • constantinoi Salazar, 1991. Type loc.: Tatabro River, 100m, Anchicayá, Valle, Costa Pacifica, Colombia (MHNUC; paratypes: CFC).   • diatonica (Fruhstorfer, 1912); original combination: Metamandana dido diatonica. Type loc.: San Pedro Sula, Honduras (BMNH). Distr.: Mexico to Panama. Up to 1,110m above sea level. Distr.: Eastern coast of Brazil from Rio Grande do Norte south into Uruguay and Northern Argentina. Host plants: Passiflora caerulea, P. elegans, P. mansoni, P. mucronata, P. rhamnifolia, P. sidaefolia, P. suberosa, P. actinia (Brown & Mielke, 1972; Benson et al., 1976; Brown, 1992; Beccaloni et al., 2008) in Brazil. P. quadrangularis and P. caerulea in Uruguay (Biezanko et al., 1974). Refs.: Röber (1906): 177. Ety.: H. Wernicke (Blasewitz, Germany)

Genus Podotricha

Genus: Podotricha Michener, 1942

Type species: Podotricha judith (Guérin-Méneville, [1844]); original combination: Colaenis euchroia Doubleday [1847]

Synonyms: None

Classification: Forewing: the posterior corner (tornus) is supported by Cu2 rather than A. Hindwing: the base of M2 is transverse.

References: Michener (1942 a): 3 (taxonomy)

    • ssp. judith (Guérin-Méneville [1844]); original combination: Cethosia judith. Type loc.: Colombia. Refs.: Guérin-Méneville and Cuvier (1844): 477. Ety.: not stated

      • syn. euchroia (Doubleday [1847]). Type loc.: Colombia. Refs.: Doubleday ([1847]): 149, pl. 20, fig. 3; Ackery and Smiles (1976) pl. 2.

    • ssp. mellosa (Stichel, 1906); original combination: Colaenis euchoria mellosa. Type loc.: Ecuador. Distr.: Northwestern Ecuador (such as Quito Rio Verde). Refs.: Stichel (1906): 208. Ety.: not stated

    • ssp. straminea (Riley, 1926); original combination: Colaenis euchroia straminea. Type loc.: Ecuador: Balsapamba. Refs.: Riley (1926): 242. Ety.: straw-coloured hindwing submarginal spots

Tribe Vagrantini

Type genus: ?

Classification: The tribe Vagrantini is divided into ten genera: Algia, Algiachroa, Cirrochroa, Cupha, Lachnoptera, Phalanta, Smerina, Terinos, Vagrans and Vindula
